{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625572"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:26:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:26:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17037"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17037"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.05,0.68,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9727"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70409"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9727"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55873"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5266"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22886"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70409"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETrimethoprim is an important antimicrobial agent commonly used to treat urinary tract infections.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of trimethoprim?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks bacterial protein synthesis","Disrupts bacterial cell membrane integrity","Inhibits bacterial cell wall synthesis","Inhibits bacterial dihydrofolate reductase","Interferes with bacterial DNA gyrase"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETrimethoprim works by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting bacterial dihydrofolate reductase\u003C/strong\u003E, an essential enzyme in folate metabolism. This prevents the production of tetrahydrofolate from dihydrofolate, which is necessary for the synthesis of purines and thymidine. Without these building blocks, bacteria cannot synthesise DNA and thus cannot replicate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking bacterial protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with aminoglycosides and tetracyclines, which act on bacterial ribosomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisruption of bacterial cell membrane integrity\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action for polymyxins, which interfere with cell membrane phospholipids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of bacterial cell wall synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is how beta-lactam antibiotics work by preventing peptidoglycan cross-linking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterference with bacterial DNA gyrase\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of fluoroquinolones, which prevent DNA supercoiling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETrimethoprim\u0027s selective toxicity comes from its approximately 50,000 times greater affinity for bacterial dihydrofolate reductase compared to the human enzyme.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trimethoprim inhibits dihydrofolate reductase, preventing the conversion of dihydrofolate to tetrahydrofolate.","Tetrahydrofolate is essential for the synthesis of purines and thymidine, which are required for DNA synthesis.","Trimethoprim has greater affinity for bacterial dihydrofolate reductase compared to human enzyme, making it selectively toxic to bacteria."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55873"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17037"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55873"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T22:41:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T22:42:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9727"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70409"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"update